1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:32,280
The speaker quotes Scripture, tells stories, and uses proper punctuation, capitalization,

2
00:00:32,300 --> 00:00:34,680
looking for olives and, you know, the sweet gherkins and stuff,

3
00:00:34,820 --> 00:00:36,900
and flip-flopping around in the Ralphs.

4
00:00:36,920 --> 00:00:37,940
And I thought, this is fun.

5
00:00:38,100 --> 00:00:39,020
This is why we live here.

6
00:00:39,100 --> 00:00:40,000
Praise God.

7
00:00:41,120 --> 00:00:44,080
Because my buddy back east is always trying to get me to move to Ohio,

8
00:00:44,180 --> 00:00:46,420
and I always ask him, hey, Steve, what's temperature outside?

9
00:00:46,560 --> 00:00:48,000
He goes, oh, it's, you know, 4.

10
00:00:48,680 --> 00:00:52,940
And I go, yeah, it's about 84 here, pal, so stick it in your ear.

11
00:00:53,580 --> 00:00:56,420
Anyway, we have a great relationship.

12
00:00:56,480 --> 00:00:57,580
We can say stuff like that.

13
00:00:58,620 --> 00:01:00,420
And I am grateful that I'm here.

14
00:01:00,580 --> 00:01:02,100
I'm grateful to be in this church.

15
00:01:02,100 --> 00:01:06,100
I'm grateful to have the friends and the family that I do, and I've been thinking about gratitude

16
00:01:06,100 --> 00:01:09,760
a lot as we move into Thanksgiving. And I want to start by just sharing

17
00:01:09,760 --> 00:01:12,920
about a gentleman that you may have heard of. He was

18
00:01:12,920 --> 00:01:18,630
lived in from 1865 to 1936.

19
00:01:18,950 --> 00:01:22,770
He was English and born in Bombay, India. He wrote

20
00:01:22,770 --> 00:01:26,790
poetry and the author of Captain Courageous, How the

21
00:01:26,790 --> 00:01:30,410
Leopard Got His Spots, and you all know this from Disney, The Jungle Books.

22
00:01:31,170 --> 00:01:31,730
Who is he?

23
00:01:32,770 --> 00:01:33,450
Rudyard Kipling.

24
00:01:34,860 --> 00:01:37,680
Now, Kipling's writings made him famous.

25
00:01:38,420 --> 00:01:42,700
And there was a gentleman newspaper reporter who said,

26
00:01:42,700 --> 00:01:49,150
Mr. Kipling, I have just calculated the money that you make and so forth,

27
00:01:49,190 --> 00:01:51,970
and I figure that you're making about $100 per word.

28
00:01:53,700 --> 00:01:56,240
That's pretty good money, especially in that day and age.

29
00:01:56,920 --> 00:02:00,900
And so the reporter pulled out a $100 bill and said,

30
00:02:00,900 --> 00:02:04,120
well, Mr. Kipling, why don't you give me one of those $100 words?

31
00:02:05,320 --> 00:02:09,740
At which point Mr. Kipling took the $100 bill, put it in his pocket, and said, thanks.

32
00:02:13,970 --> 00:02:16,670
But that word is a $100 word, isn't it?

33
00:02:17,070 --> 00:02:21,650
It's a million-dollar word because it says so much.

34
00:02:22,570 --> 00:02:26,630
And when it's not said, that also says so much.

35
00:02:27,570 --> 00:02:30,830
You can hurt people by keeping thanks back.

36
00:02:30,830 --> 00:02:37,030
and you can bless people in so many innumerable ways by saying thanks.

37
00:02:38,350 --> 00:02:41,830
I have to confess, writing this message, I was really convicted

38
00:02:41,830 --> 00:02:44,490
because I don't say thanks enough to the people around me either.

39
00:02:45,230 --> 00:02:50,710
I tend to just go from item to item, issue to issue, event to event, and so I apologize.

40
00:02:51,570 --> 00:02:53,830
I tend to be a steamroller and I need to say thanks.

41
00:02:54,130 --> 00:02:57,730
So I'm convicted as I preach and share as well.

42
00:02:58,690 --> 00:03:03,190
Well, moving into Thanksgiving season, I want us to think about our attitude of gratitude.

43
00:03:03,410 --> 00:03:06,250
Do we have that embedded in our souls?

44
00:03:07,530 --> 00:03:10,730
And there's one way to evaluate that and to be challenged by that,

45
00:03:10,730 --> 00:03:16,670
and it comes from a drama between Jesus and some leprous men that he encounters.

46
00:03:17,920 --> 00:03:20,960
And I want us to think about our own degree of gratitude as we look at this.

47
00:03:21,360 --> 00:03:24,100
From Luke chapter 17, it's on the screen behind me.

48
00:03:24,100 --> 00:03:32,890
As Jesus continued on toward Jerusalem, he reached the border between Galilee and Samaria.

49
00:03:33,590 --> 00:03:38,270
And as he entered a village there, ten lepers stood at a distance crying out,

50
00:03:38,390 --> 00:03:42,430
Jesus, Master, have mercy on us.

51
00:03:44,700 --> 00:03:48,970
He looked at them and he said, go, show yourselves to the priests.

52
00:03:50,210 --> 00:03:52,650
And as they went, the leprosy disappeared.

53
00:03:54,540 --> 00:03:59,240
Now one of them, when he saw that he was healed, came back to Jesus shouting,

54
00:03:59,580 --> 00:04:01,220
Praise God, I'm healed!

55
00:04:02,880 --> 00:04:08,260
And he fell face down on the ground at Jesus' feet, thanking him for what he had done.

56
00:04:09,630 --> 00:04:12,020
This man was a Samaritan.

57
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:16,220
And Jesus asked, Didn't I heal ten men?

58
00:04:17,420 --> 00:04:18,620
Where are the other nine?

59
00:04:18,620 --> 00:04:23,270
Does only the foreigner return to give God the glory?

60
00:04:24,150 --> 00:04:26,270
And Jesus said to the man, Stand up and go.

61
00:04:26,270 --> 00:04:28,790
Your faith has made you well.

62
00:04:31,100 --> 00:04:35,890
Jesus, walking on a border town between Samaria and Galilee.

63
00:04:37,220 --> 00:04:43,060
And like any border community, you find people of both sides intermingled in that community.

64
00:04:44,310 --> 00:04:45,210
And the same is here.

65
00:04:45,290 --> 00:04:47,170
We find Samaritans and Jews.

66
00:04:47,450 --> 00:04:52,330
Yet, of the men who were afflicted, these ten men were separate in religion,

67
00:04:52,330 --> 00:04:58,360
they were separate in culture, but they were united in misery.

68
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:06,450
For they had leprosy, the most feared illness of the day.

69
00:05:08,180 --> 00:05:16,800
Now, biblically, leprosy can cover a multitude of skin diseases, rashes, sores, scales, eruptions, all kinds of things,

70
00:05:17,160 --> 00:05:24,080
including what we now call Hansen's disease, which is truly leprosy as we know it.

71
00:05:25,160 --> 00:05:29,580
And this is an awful disease because the reality is this.

72
00:05:29,580 --> 00:05:33,660
You lose the feeling in the extremities of your body.

73
00:05:34,460 --> 00:05:41,600
And when you lose the feeling, then you don't know whether you've bruised your hands or feet or your legs and arms.

74
00:05:41,820 --> 00:05:45,120
You can't discern if you're hurting yourself.

75
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:48,060
You step on a tack and you don't know it.

76
00:05:50,460 --> 00:05:53,680
You can practically cut your finger off and you don't know it.

77
00:05:53,680 --> 00:06:13,510
Now with this disease, when you live with that, your body decays, and you live with stench and sores and secretions, and you live with leprosy in alienation because as you entered a public place, you had to cry out by the law.

78
00:06:13,510 --> 00:06:25,670
you had to say unclean unclean and then everybody gets out of your way all the time a leper was

79
00:06:25,670 --> 00:06:32,070
bereft of human touch a leper was denied dignity children and others always pointing

80
00:06:32,070 --> 00:06:43,970
eww leprosy laughing ridiculing you and certainly scurrying at your sight a leper was denied him

81
00:06:43,970 --> 00:06:48,670
making a living you can't work with leprosy nobody's going to hire you nobody's going to

82
00:06:48,670 --> 00:06:52,250
buy your product. And so you lived by

83
00:06:52,250 --> 00:06:59,040
begging or stealing. It was a life of misery and

84
00:06:59,040 --> 00:07:03,450
loneliness. No touch from a spouse. No time with your

85
00:07:03,450 --> 00:07:08,600
children. No Saturday soccer games. No dance

86
00:07:08,600 --> 00:07:12,400
classes. No piano recitals. No job. No

87
00:07:12,400 --> 00:07:16,480
fulfillment from work. No life in the mainstream of society. You are

88
00:07:16,480 --> 00:07:21,680
condemned to a life of death and death alone. So these

89
00:07:21,680 --> 00:07:28,500
ten men live in this hopeless abandonment. And so desperate times necessitates desperate

90
00:07:28,500 --> 00:07:34,860
measures, and so Samaritans and Jews, separate in religion, separate in culture, united in

91
00:07:34,860 --> 00:07:44,550
misery, for misery loves company. And they come together. And then they see him. He's

92
00:07:44,550 --> 00:07:52,200
the one we've heard can do miracles. He can heal us. Jesus, Master, have mercy on us.

93
00:07:54,200 --> 00:07:55,740
And Jesus hears their cries.

94
00:07:56,920 --> 00:07:58,540
Jesus has compassion on them.

95
00:07:59,060 --> 00:08:03,060
Jesus has such power that by his very words, they're healed.

96
00:08:05,580 --> 00:08:08,780
And they're instructed to journey, to head towards the priests.

97
00:08:11,200 --> 00:08:14,880
Because the priests are the ones who determine who's clean and unclean.

98
00:08:15,420 --> 00:08:17,920
Go to the priests and show yourselves healed.

99
00:08:19,510 --> 00:08:20,130
And the men obey.

100
00:08:21,240 --> 00:08:23,560
Jews and Samaritans alike, they obey Jesus.

101
00:08:23,560 --> 00:08:25,520
They head off toward the priests.

102
00:08:25,520 --> 00:08:28,600
and on the way, they're healed.

103
00:08:30,300 --> 00:08:31,040
Can you believe it?

104
00:08:31,060 --> 00:08:31,720
Just like that.

105
00:08:33,120 --> 00:08:33,700
They're healed.

106
00:08:34,460 --> 00:08:36,860
And only one comes back to give thanks.

107
00:08:40,270 --> 00:08:41,530
I don't know if you realize it or not,

108
00:08:42,410 --> 00:08:45,710
but Friday is the biggest shopping day

109
00:08:45,710 --> 00:08:46,810
for Christmas coming up.

110
00:08:46,870 --> 00:08:47,270
Do you know that?

111
00:08:47,890 --> 00:08:48,290
Are you ready?

112
00:08:51,330 --> 00:08:51,950
I mean, it's here.

113
00:08:52,070 --> 00:08:54,430
30 some odd days, we're tearing packages open.

114
00:08:54,490 --> 00:08:55,630
I'm a restrained person.

115
00:08:55,970 --> 00:08:57,370
However, there have been times

116
00:08:57,370 --> 00:08:59,470
under the Christmas tree

117
00:08:59,470 --> 00:09:02,270
where I have not been restrained.

118
00:09:03,570 --> 00:09:07,430
I mean, nowadays I'm really respectable and, oh, who's this from?

119
00:09:07,470 --> 00:09:08,290
And, oh, I write it down.

120
00:09:08,310 --> 00:09:09,410
I'm the list keeper now.

121
00:09:10,210 --> 00:09:12,630
You know, I keep track of everything it's from.

122
00:09:13,210 --> 00:09:17,930
When I was little, you know, you obsess on the presence under the tree, don't you?

123
00:09:17,930 --> 00:09:22,630
I mean, every day you cruise by the tree and you shake a few things

124
00:09:22,630 --> 00:09:26,960
and you peel that tape back just a bit, just a bit,

125
00:09:27,720 --> 00:09:31,200
and you can see the G.I. Joe or whatever's in there and, oh, yes.

126
00:09:32,080 --> 00:09:33,040
You get so excited.

127
00:09:33,420 --> 00:09:39,420
And it's really hard not to just really obsess on the tree.

128
00:09:39,420 --> 00:09:43,220
And then when finally Christmas morning or Christmas Eve, depending on your tradition,

129
00:09:44,750 --> 00:09:48,850
pell-mell, right, boom, right to the tree, ripping stuff off.

130
00:09:49,540 --> 00:09:52,060
And mom or dad says, oh, and who is that from?

131
00:09:55,330 --> 00:09:57,610
And you dig back to the wrappings, right?

132
00:09:59,180 --> 00:09:59,620
Right?

133
00:09:59,980 --> 00:10:01,000
Oh, here's the tag.

134
00:10:01,060 --> 00:10:02,540
I think that went with this one.

135
00:10:03,340 --> 00:10:07,020
And you send, you know, thank yous to the wrong people and stuff, right?

136
00:10:07,020 --> 00:10:12,300
When you get excited about the gift, it's easy to forget the giver.

137
00:10:13,730 --> 00:10:18,770
It is possible that these ten men on their way, limping toward the priests,

138
00:10:19,940 --> 00:10:22,680
dragging their feet and their arms and struggling,

139
00:10:23,040 --> 00:10:27,200
and suddenly the pus dries up and the scales are placed back where they should be,

140
00:10:27,320 --> 00:10:31,140
and things begin to get healed, and they get excited, and they start running.

141
00:10:32,080 --> 00:10:37,140
And it's possible in their excitement that they go running to hug their children

142
00:10:37,140 --> 00:10:42,420
and to go grab their spouses and to be, I'm healed.

143
00:10:44,730 --> 00:10:47,750
It's possible that they forget completely how they got healed.

144
00:10:48,880 --> 00:10:50,020
I can imagine that.

145
00:10:51,280 --> 00:10:54,040
I've been so excited I've forgotten where the gift came from.

146
00:10:54,800 --> 00:10:55,620
It is possible.

147
00:10:57,400 --> 00:11:01,500
A more cynical approach could be this.

148
00:11:03,560 --> 00:11:05,900
Maybe one wanted to see if the cure was real.

149
00:11:09,060 --> 00:11:11,320
Maybe one wanted to see if it would last.

150
00:11:13,720 --> 00:11:15,580
Maybe one said he'd go see Jesus later.

151
00:11:17,750 --> 00:11:20,590
Maybe one decided he never had leprosy.

152
00:11:20,770 --> 00:11:23,170
It really wasn't what it was.

153
00:11:25,610 --> 00:11:27,570
Maybe one said he would have gotten well anyway.

154
00:11:31,080 --> 00:11:33,120
Maybe one gave the glory to the priests.

155
00:11:36,300 --> 00:11:39,980
Maybe one said, well, Jesus didn't really do anything.

156
00:11:40,100 --> 00:11:41,600
All he did was tell me to go.

157
00:11:44,430 --> 00:11:46,590
Maybe one said any rabbi can do that.

158
00:11:47,050 --> 00:11:51,590
Maybe one said, well, I was getting better anyway.

159
00:11:54,500 --> 00:11:56,440
And those are all just excuses, aren't they?

160
00:11:58,190 --> 00:12:01,730
We sometimes offer excuses like that for our lack of gratitude.

161
00:12:02,800 --> 00:12:07,720
We might be really excited and forget, or we might just be offering excuses.

162
00:12:07,720 --> 00:12:12,940
Either way, only one of them came back, and it was the Samaritan,

163
00:12:14,300 --> 00:12:16,900
the one who's not supposed to connect with the Jews,

164
00:12:17,160 --> 00:12:20,600
the one that was separate in religion and separate in culture.

165
00:12:21,520 --> 00:12:24,040
See, Jews and Samaritans thought the other one was the pig.

166
00:12:26,920 --> 00:12:30,040
And the Samaritan comes back to Jesus, the Jewish rabbi.

167
00:12:30,400 --> 00:12:32,180
It offers thanks.

168
00:12:35,940 --> 00:12:39,400
I think it's instructive that Jesus, the Jew, heals the Samaritan.

169
00:12:40,420 --> 00:12:48,860
I think we can see there, friends, a church being formed of different races, different kinds of people.

170
00:12:51,660 --> 00:12:54,900
And I think for that, we have much to be thankful for.

171
00:12:55,850 --> 00:13:01,230
All races, all languages, all kinds of people are candidates for the love of God.

172
00:13:03,420 --> 00:13:08,720
And I want to say to you this morning, if you've ever been put on the shelf or felt

173
00:13:08,720 --> 00:13:13,240
marginalized by our society, Jesus says, you can become part of my church.

174
00:13:13,740 --> 00:13:20,960
If you've ever felt railroaded by race or color or culture, Jesus says, you can come

175
00:13:20,960 --> 00:13:22,460
and become part of my church.

176
00:13:25,140 --> 00:13:29,480
Because we've all been condemned by our disobedience and our sin.

177
00:13:30,300 --> 00:13:34,860
And then when forgiven by Jesus Christ and empowered by the Holy Spirit, we have much

178
00:13:34,860 --> 00:13:35,880
to be thankful for.

179
00:13:39,520 --> 00:13:41,980
The lepers here were healed of their leprosy.

180
00:13:44,060 --> 00:13:46,660
But the Samaritan came back and he gave God glory.

181
00:13:48,640 --> 00:13:51,020
And Jesus said, your faith has made you well.

182
00:13:53,290 --> 00:13:57,270
That word there, made you well, in the original language has a double meaning.

183
00:13:57,570 --> 00:14:01,830
It means physical healing, but it also has an undercurrent of salvation.

184
00:14:04,440 --> 00:14:06,420
Nine of them were healed of leprosy.

185
00:14:06,420 --> 00:14:09,720
One came back and was made well spiritually.

186
00:14:11,500 --> 00:14:12,760
Your faith has made you well.

187
00:14:15,760 --> 00:14:19,180
The God of the universe healed physically and spiritually as well.

188
00:14:19,500 --> 00:14:22,840
The kingdom of God was at work amongst these ten,

189
00:14:23,200 --> 00:14:26,640
and only one acknowledges that God is at work.

190
00:14:27,020 --> 00:14:29,060
Friends, God is moving in your lives.

191
00:14:29,380 --> 00:14:30,500
Do you give him thanks?

192
00:14:34,410 --> 00:14:38,470
Is your heart filled with grace and gratitude for what God has done in your life?

193
00:14:41,080 --> 00:14:45,790
Do you thank God for your families, your friends, your homes, your goods?

194
00:14:45,790 --> 00:14:52,510
Do you give back to God in the form of the tithe as a thank offering?

195
00:14:55,740 --> 00:14:59,400
Do you regularly make thanking God a part of your prayer life?

196
00:15:04,610 --> 00:15:08,740
There was a Bible scholar named H.A. Ironside who was in a crowded restaurant.

197
00:15:11,470 --> 00:15:15,530
And as he's about to sit down at his place for the meal, a gentleman approaches and says,

198
00:15:15,610 --> 00:15:16,810
May I share the table with you?

199
00:15:17,680 --> 00:15:18,720
And he says, By all means.

200
00:15:18,800 --> 00:15:19,740
And they sit together.

201
00:15:21,320 --> 00:15:26,460
And Ironside puts his head forward and closes his eyes and begins to pray.

202
00:15:28,120 --> 00:15:31,340
And the man says, do you have a headache?

203
00:15:34,080 --> 00:15:34,700
He said, no.

204
00:15:36,200 --> 00:15:37,680
Well, is there something wrong with your food?

205
00:15:39,470 --> 00:15:43,350
No, I was simply thanking God, as I always do before I eat.

206
00:15:44,580 --> 00:15:46,620
And the man said, oh, you're one of those.

207
00:15:48,280 --> 00:15:50,860
And he said, I want you to know I never give thanks.

208
00:15:51,560 --> 00:15:54,620
I earn my money by the sweat of my brow,

209
00:15:54,920 --> 00:15:58,270
and I don't have to give thanks to anybody when I eat.

210
00:15:58,270 --> 00:15:59,670
I just start right in.

211
00:16:01,360 --> 00:16:03,460
And Ironside says, oh, you're like my dog.

212
00:16:05,100 --> 00:16:13,370
That's what he does too. It's funny how sometimes we can just sort of start right into things

213
00:16:13,370 --> 00:16:26,440
and forget to give thanks, can't we? Woof. The reality is that God gives blessing and grace

214
00:16:26,440 --> 00:16:32,760
to everyone on this planet. In fact, we can't even move and live and have our being without God's

215
00:16:32,760 --> 00:16:40,280
very presence giving us life. The Bible says in Matthew 5 45, for he gives his sunlight to both

216
00:16:40,280 --> 00:16:44,440
the evil and the good. He sends rain on the just and the unjust

217
00:16:44,440 --> 00:16:49,740
too. In Luke 6.35, love your enemies

218
00:16:49,740 --> 00:16:52,760
and do good to them, says Jesus. Lend to them.

219
00:16:53,520 --> 00:16:58,050
And don't be concerned what they might not repay. Then your reward from heaven

220
00:16:58,050 --> 00:17:02,040
will be very great. And you'll truly be acting as children

221
00:17:02,040 --> 00:17:05,940
of the Most High. For He is kind to the unthankful and to

222
00:17:05,940 --> 00:17:10,680
those who are wicked. God gives a grace just allowing us

223
00:17:10,680 --> 00:17:14,830
to live and enjoy the earth and enjoy good things in life

224
00:17:14,830 --> 00:17:18,730
whether we know God or not. We who know God ought to be

225
00:17:18,730 --> 00:17:21,610
that much more full of grace and mercy.

226
00:17:22,630 --> 00:17:26,650
People like the Samaritan who worships God with deep reverence and a soul

227
00:17:26,650 --> 00:17:30,890
filling gratitude because we know the author of all good things.

228
00:17:36,190 --> 00:17:38,990
The story is told of two friends bumping into each other on the street

229
00:17:38,990 --> 00:17:44,100
and one is looking very sad on the verge of tears.

230
00:17:45,780 --> 00:17:47,740
The friend asked, what in the world is wrong?

231
00:17:49,740 --> 00:17:50,540
He said, well, let me tell you.

232
00:17:50,580 --> 00:17:53,840
Three weeks ago, my uncle died and left me $40,000.

233
00:17:54,800 --> 00:17:56,800
That's a lot of money.

234
00:17:58,560 --> 00:18:04,740
Well, but two weeks ago, my cousin that I never even knew died and left me $85,000 free and clear.

235
00:18:06,960 --> 00:18:08,020
Sounds like you've been blessed.

236
00:18:08,200 --> 00:18:09,280
Well, he said, you don't understand.

237
00:18:10,280 --> 00:18:12,060
Last week, my great aunt passed away.

238
00:18:12,120 --> 00:18:13,860
I inherited almost a quarter of a million.

239
00:18:16,000 --> 00:18:17,480
Now, this guy's really confused.

240
00:18:19,010 --> 00:18:20,410
Why do you look so glum?

241
00:18:21,550 --> 00:18:23,430
He said, this week, nothing.

242
00:18:27,980 --> 00:18:31,500
You see, that's the problem with receiving something on a regular basis, isn't it?

243
00:18:31,500 --> 00:18:35,080
We get used to it, even if it's a gift.

244
00:18:36,700 --> 00:18:37,560
We take it for granted.

245
00:18:38,220 --> 00:18:40,970
That's very silly, but you get the idea.

246
00:18:43,100 --> 00:18:45,780
That's why it's good for our nation to take some time once a year

247
00:18:45,780 --> 00:18:49,440
and just take stock of what we have and to give thanks.

248
00:18:50,690 --> 00:18:52,770
But why should we stop only once a year?

249
00:18:54,290 --> 00:18:59,600
What about once a month, once a week, or once a day?

250
00:19:03,560 --> 00:19:10,180
I think when we become aware of our blessings and become thankful each and every day,

251
00:19:10,180 --> 00:19:13,780
it keeps our hearts soft and our souls are pointed in the right direction.

252
00:19:14,380 --> 00:19:18,800
I also know that attitude of gratitude is like an oil that lubricates relationships.

253
00:19:19,040 --> 00:19:20,840
It keeps things moving and humming along.

254
00:19:21,860 --> 00:19:27,320
Co-workers, friends, spouses, are you blessing each other and giving thanks for each other?

255
00:19:28,340 --> 00:19:29,980
Do you thank each other for what they've done?

256
00:19:31,480 --> 00:19:32,420
Or do you take it for granted?

257
00:19:33,790 --> 00:19:35,450
And in essence, use other people.

258
00:19:38,170 --> 00:19:41,570
I think the attitude of gratitude is important for our spirituality as well.

259
00:19:42,030 --> 00:19:44,130
For it affects our relationship with God.

260
00:19:45,380 --> 00:19:48,960
You see, the attitude of gratitude will keep us in touch with Him more.

261
00:19:49,200 --> 00:19:51,440
It tunes us into the way things really are.

262
00:19:52,080 --> 00:19:53,500
Without Him, we're nothing.

263
00:19:53,880 --> 00:20:00,140
You can ask yourself, well, is giving thanks all that really important?

264
00:20:00,260 --> 00:20:01,000
I would say yes.

265
00:20:02,410 --> 00:20:06,750
In fact, the Bible says it's one of the evidences that you are actually controlled by the Holy Spirit

266
00:20:06,750 --> 00:20:09,250
is if you have an attitude of thanksgiving in your heart.

267
00:20:11,060 --> 00:20:13,040
Ephesians 5, verse 20 says,

268
00:20:13,040 --> 00:20:16,620
Let the Holy Spirit fill and control you.

269
00:20:18,260 --> 00:20:22,540
Then you will sing psalms and hymns and spiritual songs amongst yourselves,

270
00:20:22,860 --> 00:20:25,200
making music to the Lord in your hearts.

271
00:20:25,820 --> 00:20:29,000
And then you will always give thanks for everything to God,

272
00:20:29,700 --> 00:20:31,880
the Father, in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ.

273
00:20:34,540 --> 00:20:37,200
See, when you're filled with the Holy Spirit and your spirit is in touch with God,

274
00:20:37,420 --> 00:20:40,190
you become thankful all the time.

275
00:20:42,200 --> 00:20:44,080
It's one evidence that God is moving in your life,

276
00:20:44,140 --> 00:20:46,120
that you have a heart that's thankful.

277
00:20:48,630 --> 00:20:51,090
In fact, it's God's will for us that we be a people of thanks.

278
00:20:51,210 --> 00:20:53,630
In 1 Thessalonians 5.18, Paul writes,

279
00:20:53,630 --> 00:20:57,460
No matter what happens, always be thankful,

280
00:20:58,600 --> 00:21:01,800
for this is God's will for you who belong to Christ Jesus.

281
00:21:03,980 --> 00:21:06,520
So the Christian life is a life of gratitude.

282
00:21:07,160 --> 00:21:07,560
That's right.

283
00:21:12,030 --> 00:21:13,310
Do you know what's powerful about that?

284
00:21:15,760 --> 00:21:17,660
It keeps our hearts soft towards the Lord.

285
00:21:18,810 --> 00:21:20,870
It keeps our hearts soft towards each other.

286
00:21:23,340 --> 00:21:24,480
It makes life better.

287
00:21:25,780 --> 00:21:29,150
And we live a life of gratitude and thanksgiving.

288
00:21:30,260 --> 00:21:33,820
And so my encouragement is this week not to make it a once-a-year experience,

289
00:21:34,630 --> 00:21:38,150
but to make gratitude and thanksgiving an everyday experience.

290
00:21:39,260 --> 00:21:41,680
Part of your prayer life every day is to begin,

291
00:21:41,680 --> 00:21:45,340
Thank you, Father, for all that you've given me.

292
00:21:46,880 --> 00:21:50,460
Whether I'm in a good place right now in life or a tough place right now,

293
00:21:50,700 --> 00:21:53,260
thank you for the blessings that you have given to me.

294
00:21:56,070 --> 00:21:58,970
And friends, you'll watch your life with God deepen,

295
00:21:59,510 --> 00:22:00,910
your love for him will deepen,

296
00:22:02,260 --> 00:22:05,800
and your relationships with others will deepen as well.

297
00:22:07,240 --> 00:22:08,780
The attitude of gratitude is powerful.

298
00:22:09,360 --> 00:22:11,700
God has touched your life in so many profound ways.

299
00:22:12,060 --> 00:22:14,440
Will you go back and give him thanks?

300
00:22:15,390 --> 00:22:16,430
Will you be the one?

301
00:22:18,310 --> 00:22:19,010
Will you be the one?

302
00:22:21,280 --> 00:22:24,000
As we think about that, I want us to read together this psalm.

303
00:22:24,650 --> 00:22:25,570
I'm going to invite you to stand.

304
00:22:25,830 --> 00:22:26,530
It's something a little different.

305
00:22:27,130 --> 00:22:29,250
But I want us to interact with this scripture together.

306
00:22:30,560 --> 00:22:32,740
And then after this, they're going to sing,

307
00:22:34,020 --> 00:22:37,140
and we're going to have a baptism as a way of culminating our time together

308
00:22:37,140 --> 00:22:38,940
and giving thanks to our Lord.

309
00:22:40,310 --> 00:22:42,330
And I want us to read Psalm 136.

310
00:22:42,390 --> 00:22:45,170
I'm going to read the first part, and you're going to respond each time.

311
00:22:45,170 --> 00:22:47,470
And you're going to mean it from the bottom of your soul,

312
00:22:47,770 --> 00:22:49,990
His love endures forever.

313
00:22:49,990 --> 00:22:53,150
and you're going to say it over and over

314
00:22:53,150 --> 00:22:55,250
because each time you say it you're going to mean it

315
00:22:55,250 --> 00:22:57,210
a little more and a little more

316
00:22:57,210 --> 00:22:59,490
and it's going to bless your life this morning

317
00:22:59,490 --> 00:23:03,330
Psalm 136

318
00:23:03,330 --> 00:23:04,950
Give thanks to the Lord

319
00:23:04,950 --> 00:23:06,890
for He is good

320
00:23:06,890 --> 00:23:09,590
His love endures forever

321
00:23:09,590 --> 00:23:12,050
Give thanks to the God of gods

322
00:23:12,050 --> 00:23:14,450
His love endures forever

323
00:23:14,450 --> 00:23:16,470
Give thanks to the Lord of lords

324
00:23:16,470 --> 00:23:19,810
to Him who alone

325
00:23:19,810 --> 00:23:21,010
does great wonders

326
00:23:21,010 --> 00:23:24,440
who by His understanding

327
00:23:24,440 --> 00:23:34,280
made the heavens, who spread out the earth upon the waters, who made the great lights,

328
00:23:36,270 --> 00:23:45,910
the sun to govern the day, the moon and the stars to govern the night, to him who struck

329
00:23:45,910 --> 00:23:55,260
down the firstborn of Egypt, and brought Israel out from among them, with a mighty hand and

330
00:23:55,260 --> 00:24:04,930
an outstretched arm, to him who divided the Red Sea asunder and brought Israel through

331
00:24:04,930 --> 00:24:14,290
the midst of it, but swept Pharaoh and the army into the Red Sea, to him who led his

332
00:24:14,290 --> 00:24:25,170
people through the desert, who struck down great kings and killed mighty kings, Sihon

333
00:24:25,170 --> 00:24:36,970
king of the Amorites, and Og king of Bashan, and gave their land as an inheritance, an

334
00:24:36,970 --> 00:24:46,390
inheritance to his servant Israel, to the one who remembered us in our low estate, and

335
00:24:46,390 --> 00:24:55,850
freed us from our enemies, and who gives food to every creature, give thanks to the

336
00:24:55,850 --> 00:25:01,650
God of heaven. His love endures forever. Amen.

